05661nam a22008535i 9780824864729DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20062006hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1029834808  a(OCoLC)1032676778  a(OCoLC)1037982019  a(OCoLC)1041921531  a(OCoLC)1046609554  a(OCoLC)1047029806  a(OCoLC)1049674729  a(OCoLC)1054867550  a97808248647297 a10.1515/97808248647292doi  a(DE-B1597)483934  a(OCoLC)1024019257  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aHQ1745.8b.A683 2006 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a305.40959/09032221 aAndaya, Barbara Watson, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Flaming Womb :bRepositioning Women in Early Modern Southeast Asia /cBarbara Watson Andaya. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b5 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Women and “Southeast Asia” -- tChapter 2. Early Modernity, Sources, and Women’s History -- tChapter 3. Women and Religious Change -- tChapter 4. Women and Economic Change -- tChapter 5. States, Subjects, and Households -- tChapter 6. Women, Courts, and Class -- tChapter 7. Being Female in “Early Modern” Southeast Asia -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"The Princess of the Flaming Womb," the Javanese legend that introduces this pioneering study, symbolizes the many ambiguities attached to femaleness in Southeast Asian societies. Yet despite these ambiguities, the relatively egalitarian nature of male–female relations in Southeast Asia is central to arguments claiming a coherent identity for the region. This challenging work by senior scholar Barbara Watson Andaya considers such contradictions while offering a thought-provoking view of Southeast Asian history that focuses on women’s roles and perceptions. Andaya explores the broad themes of the early modern era (1500–1800)—the introduction of new religions, major economic shifts, changing patterns of state control, the impact of elite lifestyles and behaviors—drawing on an extraordinary range of sources and citing numerous examples from Thai, Vietnamese, Burmese, Philippine, and Malay societies. In the process, she provides a timely and innovative model for putting women back into world history Andaya approaches the problematic issue of "Southeast Asia" by considering ways in which topography helped describe a geo-cultural zone and contributed to regional distinctiveness in gender construction. She examines the degree to which world religions have been instrumental in (re)constructing conceptions of gender— an issue especially pertinent to Southeast Asian societies because of the leading role so often played by women in indigenous ritual. She also considers the effects of the expansion of long-distance trade, the incorporation of the region into a global trading network, the beginnings of cash-cropping and wage labor, and the increase in slavery on the position of women. Erudite, nuanced, and accessible, The Flaming Womb makes a major contribution to a Southeast Asia history that is both regional and global in content and perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aSex rolezSoutheast AsiaxHistory. 0aWomenxHistoryyModern period, 1600-. 0aWomenzSoutheast AsiaxHistory. 0aWomenzSoutheast AsiaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 200